        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin’s</ref> marriage to Amy Ruck (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Francis married Amy on 23 July 1874 (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Amy’s parents were Lawrence and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4118.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Mary Anne Ruck</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4117.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Lawrence Ruck’s</ref> only surviving brother was <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_7340.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Adam Joseph Ruck</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">The Rucks’ eldest son was <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6667.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Arthur Ashley Ruck</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">CD’s letter to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4117.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Lawrence Ruck</ref> has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7">The note from Hacon has not been found; see, however, the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9386.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Lubbock, 3 April 1874</ref>.</note>
